mimicry other birds

This bird was on a power line and was apparently mimicking the calls of other small (potential) prey birds. I could tentatively make out the calls of House Sparrows and sunbirds. Though a few house sparrows did fly on to the same power line and alighted near the shrike (coincidence?), the bird did not mind them and went on and on for more than five minutes before it flew off. The video can be seen here <https://youtu.be/-89SkMGrTP0>

I managed to record a number of calls and song types made by the male. Full range of calls are not well documented for the region (Wells 2007).  This is a recording of the interesting vocalisation, a warbling song that I have heard a few times. Lefranc (2011) says “The song is a pleasant, somewhat metallic warble. It contains the imitation of calls and songs of other birds. … The song can be delivered without interruption for 5, 10 or even 15 minutes.” The song is mixture of bird calls and, at times, almost like an Oriental Magpie Robin. Note that there is an anxious Yellow-vented Bulbul and some traffic noise in the background.
